<TITLE> Five remanded in arms case in Chittagong </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Chittagong, June 6 (bdnews24.com)The five arrested in the recent Chittagong arms case were put on remand for two days by the Chief Metropolitan Magistrate's Court Wednesday, police said. They were arrested Monday when the police seized a haul of guns and bullets from an abandoned rubber factory in the port city. The police applied for a seven-day remand to interrogate them, but magistrate Mokhlesur Rahman approved only two days after a brief hearing. A former security guard of the factory, Matilal Debnath, testified in court, sub-inspector Ranjan Shamonto said. Shamonto said the police had seized four rifles, two shotguns, one pistol and 309 bullets from Bangladesh Chemical Complex Private Limited, owned by Awami League senior member Afsar Uddin. Police arrested his nephew Fazlul Haque Dulal and four others. bdnews24
